<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kai}}}} is a sentence ending particle which marks a "yes/no" question in informal male speech.
The preceding sentence must be in the plain form.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{day^book^word}}wo@KJ{{exertion^strong}}suru@EM{{kai}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Will you study Japanese?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{old*boy^accomplished}}ha@KJ{{study^life}}@EM{{kai}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Are you students?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kai}}}} is only used for "yes/no" questions. For sentences involving an interrogative,
<a href="grammar-particle-dai.html">@HI{{dai}}</a> is used.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KT{{apa-to}}ha@KJ{{quiet}}ka@EM{{kai}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is this apartment quiet?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
In the sentence patterns above, the @HI{{no}} appears where formal speech would have used <a href="grammar-n-desu.html">@HI{{ndesu}}</a>.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{person}}ha@KJ{{before^life}}nano@EM{{kai}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is that person a teacher?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{sono@KJ{{book}}ha@KJ{{difficult}}shiino@EM{{kai}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is that book difficult?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The equivalent sentences in female informal speech would be formed by dropping @HI{{@EM{{kai}}}} and using a rising intonation.
</p>

